      <title>Simpson&#39;s Paradox: Understanding a Counter-Intuitive Statistical Trap</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1314/posts/simpson_paradox/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1314/posts/simpson_paradox/</guid>
      <description>&lt;img src=&#34;feature.png&#34; alt=&#34;Simpson&#39;s Paradox illustration&#34; style=&#34;width: 70%; height: auto; display: block; margin: 0 auto 2rem auto;&#34;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Simpson’s paradox is one of the most puzzling phenomena in statistics. It occurs when a trend observed in several distinct groups &lt;strong&gt;completely reverses&lt;/strong&gt; once those groups are combined. In other words, &lt;strong&gt;what appears true within each subgroup can become false when the data is analyzed as a whole&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
